    "All these evidences are summed up, so as to obtain overall evidence in favor of the positive (f (x) > 0) or the negative (f (x) < 0) class.",
    "Waegeman et al. (2009) generalized the framework to the case where training information is given in the form of pairwise preferences x i x j, encoded by the label y i, j = +1 (and y j,i = -1) attached to the tuple (x i, x j).",
    "Making use of a generalized kernel",
    "they obtain solutions of the form f (x, x) = i, j:y i, j =1 α i, j k * (x i, x j, x, x), expressing a degree of preference of x over x.",
    "Intuitively, the tuple (x, x) is compared to all \"support preferences\" x i x j in the training data, and similarity between (x, x) and (x i, x j) provides evidence in favor of the preference x x."
